## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clarified the system description section today is understanding why "what the system is" and "what the system does with sensitive data" are two different sections that both belong in the description.

"What the system is" is technical: EC2 instance, RDS MySQL database, WAF, GuardDuty, IAM configuration, VPC architecture. This is the information that an assessor or auditor uses to understand the authorization boundary and identify which controls apply.

"What the system does with sensitive data" is the mission context: patient registration, clinical encounter documentation, medication history, lab result recording, HIV status tracking, mental health notes. This is the information that explains why the system is categorized HIGH across all three security objectives and why HIPAA applies. A system that stores routine administrative data might merit different controls than one that stores mental health records and HIV status information for a vulnerable population.

The system description needs both — the technical description enables control assessment, the mission context explains the stakes. An assessor who understands the mission context will understand why the CP-2 condition was the AO's highest concern at authorization: a system that community health workers in a low-resource environment depend on for clinical decision support during patient encounters cannot afford unplanned downtime without a tested fallback procedure.

