### Authorization Boundary

**In-scope components:**

The authorization boundary encompasses all components within the MyClinic AWS account that support the OpenMRS application:

| Component | Type | Location | Purpose |
|---|---|---|---|
| EC2 instance (MCOPENMRS-EC2-01) | Compute | Private subnet, us-east-1 | OpenMRS application server |
| RDS instance (MCOPENMRS-RDS-01) | Database | Private subnet, us-east-1 | Patient record database |
| S3 backup bucket | Storage | us-east-1 (replicated to us-west-2) | Database backup and cross-region DR |
| VPC, subnets, security groups | Network | us-east-1 | Network segmentation and access control |
| WAF, ALB | Network security | Public subnet, us-east-1 | Application layer protection and routing |
| IAM users, roles, policies | Access management | AWS account-wide | Identity and access control |
| CloudTrail, CloudWatch, GuardDuty, Config, Security Hub, Inspector, Audit Manager | Monitoring | Account-wide | Continuous monitoring and detection |
| KMS keys (openmrs-rds-encryption, openmrs-ec2-encryption, openmrs-s3-backup) | Cryptography | us-east-1 | Encryption key management |

**Out-of-scope components:**

The following are explicitly out of scope for this authorization:

- Other systems in MyClinic's broader IT environment not connected to OpenMRS (HR systems, financial systems, email)
- The Laboratory Information System (LIS) is out of scope as a system — it is governed by its own authorization and security program. The LIS interconnection (HL7 interface) is in scope as an interconnection and is governed by the Information Sharing Agreement (ISA) documented in the SSP.
- Physical security of clinical workstations — workstations are used to access OpenMRS via web browser; workstation security is governed by an endpoint security policy outside this GRC plan's scope.
- AWS infrastructure security below the hypervisor level — governed by the AWS Shared Responsibility Model and assured through the AWS SOC 2 Type II report.

**Inherited controls:** Security controls for the physical data center, hardware, hypervisor, and AWS global network infrastructure are inherited from AWS and documented in the AWS SOC 2 Type II report. The AWS BAA establishes AWS's obligations as a Business Associate for ePHI processed in HIPAA-eligible services.

