## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The population-specific sensitivity section — where I explained that HIV status disclosure for patients in stigmatizing communities creates harms not captured by standard breach cost metrics — was informed by the **2013 New York State Department of Health breach** in which names and HIV status information for approximately 4,800 individuals were inadvertently disclosed in a court filing that was not properly sealed.

The harm from that disclosure was not primarily financial — it was social and personal, affecting individuals' relationships, employment, and safety. Some individuals reported significant personal consequences from the disclosure.

Standard breach impact metrics — cost per record, regulatory fine, credit monitoring cost — do not capture this category of harm. A security program for a system that stores HIV status information for a vulnerable population needs to understand that the HIPAA confidentiality HIGH categorization reflects real-world harm potential that goes beyond what the regulatory penalty structure quantifies.

For the OpenMRS GRC program, this understanding of population-specific sensitivity is what justifies the HIGH categorization and the depth of the security program — not just regulatory compliance, but genuine protection of vulnerable patients.

